@page "/help"
@inject BlogAdminOptions Options
@inject ContentTypeRegistry Registry

<PageTitle>Help — admin</PageTitle>

<header class="page-heading">
    <h1>Help</h1>
    <p class="page-heading__lede">How to manage the site from this admin.</p>
</header>

<article class="help">

<section class="help__section">
<h2>Signing in</h2>
<p>
    The admin uses a <strong>GitHub Personal Access Token</strong> (PAT) so it can commit your changes
    to the site's repository. Tokens are valid for up to a year, after which you'll need to generate a
    new one.
</p>
<ol>
    <li>Go to <a href="https://github.com/settings/personal-access-tokens" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GitHub → Settings → Developer settings → Personal access tokens → Fine-grained tokens</a> and click <em>Generate new token</em>.</li>
    <li>Repository access: <strong>Only select repositories</strong> → pick <code>@Options.Repo.Owner/@Options.Repo.Repo</code>.</li>
    <li>Permissions: set <strong>Contents</strong> to <em>Read and write</em>. Leave everything else default.</li>
    <li>Click <em>Generate token</em>, copy the value, paste it into the admin's sign-in screen.</li>
</ol>
<p>The token is stored in your browser's local storage on this device only. Sign out clears it.</p>
</section>

<hr />

<section class="help__section">
<h2>The tabs</h2>
<dl class="help__dl">
    <dt>Dashboard</dt>
    <dd>Overview with counts of every content type, plus quick "New" buttons.</dd>

    @foreach (IContentTypeDescriptor descriptor in Registry.All)
    {
        <dt>@descriptor.DisplayName</dt>
        <dd>@(string.IsNullOrEmpty(descriptor.DashboardHint) ? $"{descriptor.DisplayName} entries." : descriptor.DashboardHint)</dd>
    }

    <dt>Images</dt>
    <dd>The image library — browse what's been uploaded, upload new images, delete unused ones.</dd>

    <dt>Help</dt>
    <dd>This page.</dd>
</dl>
</section>

<hr />

<section class="help__section">
<h2>Editing an existing entry</h2>
<ol>
    <li>Click the tab for the content type.</li>
    <li>Click the entry's slug in the table to open the editor.</li>
    <li>Change whatever you need to in the form fields or the body.</li>
    <li>Click <strong>Save</strong>.</li>
</ol>
<p>The page reloads to the list. A banner appears at the bottom of the screen tracking the deploy.</p>
<p>
    <strong>Renaming:</strong> the <em>Date</em> and <em>Slug</em> fields stay editable on existing entries.
    Change either one and a confirmation line appears at the bottom of the File section showing the new
    filename. Save then writes the entry under the new name and removes the old file (two commits, both
    automatic). There is no automatic redirect. The old URL may keep working until old generated output is
    pruned, so rename only if a stale link won't matter. The home page slug (<code>index</code>) can't be renamed.
</p>
</section>

<section class="help__section">
<h2>Creating a new entry</h2>
<ol>
    <li>Click the tab for the type of content you're creating.</li>
    <li>Click the <strong>New</strong> button at the top.</li>
    <li>For dated content types, pick a date. For static pages, no date — just a slug.</li>
    <li>
        Type a slug — lowercase, words separated by hyphens. For example <code>dvorak-cello-concerto</code> rather than
        <code>Dvorak Cello Concerto</code>. This becomes part of the file name and the URL.
    </li>
    <li>Fill in the form fields and write the body.</li>
    <li>Click <strong>Save</strong>.</li>
</ol>
<p class="help__warning">
    <strong>Slug uniqueness:</strong> content types with flat URLs can't share a slug — two entries with
    the same slug in the same category will collide. The site's build will fail with a clear error if
    that happens; rename one to fix.
</p>
</section>

<section class="help__section">
<h2>Working with images</h2>
<p>
    Anywhere a form field expects an image path, there's a <strong>Pick / upload</strong> button next to
    it. Click it to:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>Pick an image that's already been uploaded (organized by folder).</li>
    <li>Upload a new image — choose any folder and pick a file from your computer.</li>
</ul>
<p>
    Uploaded images are automatically resized to a maximum of 2000 px wide and saved as JPEG. The site
    stays small and snappy even with high-resolution source photos. Original photos on your device
    aren't touched.
</p>
<p>
    Use the <strong>Images</strong> tab to browse and clean up the library. Each image has a <em>Copy path</em>
    button (puts the path in your clipboard, ready to paste into another field) and a <em>Delete</em> button.
</p>
</section>

<hr />

<section class="help__section">
<h2>After you save: the deploy banner</h2>
<p>
    When you save, a small banner appears in the bottom-left corner with the build status:
</p>
<dl class="help__dl">
    <dt>Saved. Waiting for the build to start…</dt>
    <dd>GitHub has the commit; the build hasn't been picked up yet. Usually a few seconds.</dd>

    <dt>Saved. Building the site…</dt>
    <dd>The build is running. Typically 60–90 seconds.</dd>

    <dt>Site updated — your change is live.</dt>
    <dd>Click <strong>View live</strong> to see your change on the public site.</dd>

    <dt>Build failed.</dt>
    <dd>Click <strong>View log</strong> to see what went wrong. Most common cause: a duplicate slug.</dd>
</dl>
<p>
    You don't have to wait around — the banner persists if you navigate to other admin tabs, and updates itself.
    Close it with the × when you're done.
</p>
</section>

<hr />

<section class="help__section">
<h2>Deleting</h2>
<p>
    Every list page has a <em>Delete</em> button on each row. Clicking it asks for confirmation right there in
    the row. Once you confirm, the file is removed from the repo and the next deploy drops the page from the
    site.
</p>
<p class="help__warning">
    Deletes are permanent through the admin, but the file lives in git history forever — anyone with repo
    access can restore it via the command line.
</p>
</section>

<hr />

<section class="help__section">
<h2>Common gotchas</h2>
<dl class="help__dl">
    <dt>"Save failed" with a network error</dt>
    <dd>
        Usually a token issue — sign out and back in with a fresh PAT. If the token's permissions changed
        (e.g. you accidentally removed Contents: read &amp; write), the API rejects the commit.
    </dd>

    <dt>I edited something but the site still shows the old version</dt>
    <dd>
        Browsers cache pages aggressively. Use the <strong>View live</strong> button from the deploy banner —
        it appends a cache-buster so you always see the fresh page. Or hold Shift while you reload.
    </dd>
</dl>
</section>

<hr />

<section class="help__section">
<h2>If something goes really wrong</h2>
<p>
    Open an issue on the
    <a href="https://github.com/@Options.Repo.Owner/@Options.Repo.Repo/issues" target="_blank" rel="noopener">repo</a>
    with what you were doing and the error message.
</p>
</section>

</article>
